{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 14:26:07.952943", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and approach\n- Goal: Detect anomalies, localize faulty devices, identify root causes.\n- Methods used: End-to-end reachability matrix, targeted pings, DNS resolution checks, HTTP timing tests from multiple vantage points, socket listening state and service status on web servers.\n\nHigh-level health assessment\n- Routing/OSPF core: Healthy. Cross-subnet ICMP between hosts and the server farm shows 0% loss and low RTTs. No reachability anomalies found between user subnets (10.1.1.0/24 and 10.2.1.0/24) and 10.200.0.0/24.\n- DNS: Reachable (RTT ~2–3 ms) and name resolution correct for web0.local–web3.local and web99.local on both hosts.\n- Policy segmentation: Confirmed. Backend web servers (20.200.0.0/24) are not reachable from hosts (ICMP Dest Net Unreachable from the dist router), but are reachable from the load balancer. This matches the design.\n- Load balancer service (web99.local): Consistently good performance from both hosts: TTFB ~0.26–0.45 s; total ~1.0–1.2 s.\n\nIdentified anomalies and localization\n1) Web server 2 (web2.local, 10.200.0.5) – HTTP service instability\n- Symptom: From multiple vantage points (host_1_1_1_1, host_2_1_1_1, web_server_0, dns_server, dhcp_server), repeated curl attempts to http://10.200.0.5 exhibit timeouts around 5 seconds on many tries. Successful attempts, when they occur, show elevated TTFB (1.8–3.9 s).\n- L3/L4 reachability: ICMP ping to 10.200.0.5 succeeds with low RTTs; no packet loss, meaning the network path is fine.\n- On-host inspection:\n  - netstat on web_server_2 shows 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN, Recv-Q=3 (indicates queued/unaccepted connections).\n  - systemctl reports apache2.service is inactive (dead). httpd service does not exist.\n- Localization: Fault is on web_server_2 itself (10.200.0.5), not the network.\n- Likely root cause: The expected Apache HTTP service is not running, yet something is bound to TCP/80 and is not accepting/processing connections properly (consistent with queued connections and client timeouts). This presents as intermittent/unavailable HTTP service at web2.local.\n\n2) Web server 0 (web0.local, 10.200.0.3) – Elevated application latency\n- Symptom: From both hosts and other servers, curl to http://web0.local or http://10.200.0.3 shows TTFB spikes 2.0–3.9 s, total time 2.8–4.7 s on many attempts.\n- L3/L4 reachability: Pings are consistently good (RTT ~2–3 ms), indicating the network is not the bottleneck.\n- Other servers (web1/web3) perform better, typically TTFB ~0.3–1.5 s and total ~1.1–2.3 s, under similar conditions.\n- Localization: Fault lies on web_server_0 (10.200.0.3) at the application layer (server-side processing delay), not in the network.\n- Likely root cause: Application or web service sluggishness on web_server_0 (e.g., server load, misconfiguration, or back-end delay), as network metrics are normal.\n\n3) Other components\n- Web servers 1 and 3 (10.200.0.4 and 10.200.0.6): Reachable and generally responsive. Some variance but no systemic failures observed.\n- Load balancer to backend connectivity: LB can ping backend_web_0/1/2 (20.200.0.2/3/4) with sub-millisecond RTTs; user requests to web99.local show stable performance, implying backend pool is reachable and responsive via the LB.\n\nEvidence highlights\n- DNS resolution from hosts: web0.local→10.200.0.3, web1→.4, web2→.5, web3→.6, web99→.7 (correct).\n- HTTP tests from hosts:\n  - web99.local: TTFB ~0.26–0.45 s; total ~1.0–1.2 s.\n  - web0.local: TTFB often 3.2–3.9 s; total up to ~4.7 s.\n  - web2.local: Frequent 5 s timeouts (no connect/response), occasional slow successes.\n  - web1/web3: TTFB ~0.3–1.5 s; total ~1.1–2.3 s.\n- On web_server_2:\n  - netstat: 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN with Recv-Q > 0.\n  - systemctl: apache2.service inactive (dead).\n\nConclusions\n- No OSPF/routing or interconnect anomalies detected; the core/distribution paths are healthy.\n- Security segmentation to backend servers is functioning per design.\n- Primary issues are localized to individual front-end web servers:\n  - web_server_2 (10.200.0.5): HTTP service malfunction/unavailability due to Apache not running and a non-Apache listener on port 80 that is not handling connections, causing timeouts.\n  - web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): Significant server-side latency leading to high TTFB; network path is normal, indicating application-layer slowness.\n- The load-balanced service (web99.local) remains healthy and does not show user-impacting degradations in current tests.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12224, "output_tokens": 4725, "total_tokens": 16949, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 3200}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3456}}}
